00:55:40,644 --> 00:55:44,828
You can see that Steph and I have read the rules because we raised our hands almost instantaneous.

547
00:55:48,271 --> 00:55:51,554
But acknowledging that comment, that's a great addition to this.

548
00:55:51,754 --> 00:56:02,664
The only thing I want to ask, because I sit on other commissions and we've not had this problem in the Human Rights Commission, but should we consider when we get to the

549
00:56:04,787 --> 00:56:06,309
members of the public to share comments.

550
00:56:06,490 --> 00:56:10,576
Should we put a time frame on that, a limitation, or are we against that sort of thing?

551
00:56:10,976 --> 00:56:12,619
It does come in handy in other commissions.

552
00:56:12,679 --> 00:56:20,010
We have never had that problem here in the Human Rights Commissions, but I just figured if we're going to discuss it, let's just throw that out there now and think about that.

553
00:56:23,077 --> 00:56:26,278
Chief, that's a great question.

554
00:56:26,338 --> 00:56:38,883
I mean, in my two commissions, we don't have a limit, but on the one that I sit on as strictly a liaison, there is a time limit.

555
00:56:40,524 --> 00:56:44,305
I've not experienced that problem.

556
00:56:44,385 --> 00:56:47,267
I've experienced the opposite because

557
00:56:49,755 --> 00:56:55,843
And when I say the opposite, I mean discussion of things that are not on the agenda, right?

558
00:56:55,883 --> 00:57:02,512
So it kind of throws the flow of the meeting off and you can't provide a response because you weren't prepared for it.

559
00:57:03,614 --> 00:57:05,757
That's definitely some food for thought.

560
00:57:06,097 --> 00:57:12,084
And if you get individuals who just disagree, sometimes they want to keep pressing points and you have to be able to move on.

561
00:57:12,384 --> 00:57:13,105
That's one point.

562
00:57:13,145 --> 00:57:18,691
Not that I don't think any of us are against listening to contrary points, but I do think there has to be a limit.

563
